1. LIBRARY USE AGREEMENT

By using FDK as a library within any Dependent Project — including linking,
embedding, or distributing FDK as part of a compiled application — the
project owner automatically accepts and agrees to the following terms. No
separate written agreement is required.

  a) CO-OWNERSHIP OF DEPENDENT PROJECTS

     FDK (Faded Dream Kit) is the sole and exclusive property of the Author.
     No use of FDK — as a library, tool, or in any other capacity — grants
     any individual or entity any ownership, co-ownership, or shared rights
     over FDK or any part of it, in any form, under any circumstances.

     By contrast, any Project Owner who uses FDK within a Dependent Project
     grants the Author a non-exclusive, perpetual right of co-ownership and
     binding authority over the Creative Direction of that Dependent Project,
     as fully defined in the FDK Sublicense located in the sublicense/
     directory of this repository. The Author's authority over Dependent
     Projects includes the right to issue binding Directives that the Project
     Owner must comply with. See the sublicense/ directory for the full terms.

  b) SUBLICENSE REQUIREMENT

     Any Dependent Project must include the FDK Sublicense found in the
     sublicense/ directory of this repository. The Sublicense grants the
     Author binding authority over the Creative Direction of any Dependent
     Project, including the right to issue Directives that the Project Owner
     must comply with. See the sublicense/ directory for the full terms.
     Specifically:

       — The SUBLICENSE file must be present in the project's repository
         or in a subdirectory named sublicense/.

       — The project's README or primary documentation must acknowledge
         that the project uses FDK and is subject to the FDK Sublicense.

       — If distributed as a package, the SUBLICENSE file must be included
         with that distribution.

     The FDK Sublicense is compatible with most software licenses including
     MIT, Apache 2.0, GPL v2/v3, LGPL, BSD, MPL 2.0, and most proprietary
     licenses. On matters covered by the Sublicense it always takes
     precedence over the Dependent Project's own license. On all other
     matters the Dependent Project's own license applies without restriction.

